Tshwane mayor Stevens Mokgalapa offered to take leave during the investigation into an illicitly recorded conversation apparently revealing sexual misconduct, according to DA Gauteng Caucus Leader, John Moodey. Courtesy of #DSTV403 PRETORIA - Tshwane mayor Stevens Mokgalapa volunteered to take special leave, according to Gauteng Caucus leader, John Moodey
The embattled mayor has been embroiled in a sex scandal in the city's offices with Transport MMC, Sheila Senkubuge. READ: DA to probe Tshwane mayor amid sex scandal The DA says its Federal Legal Commission will investigate and the two will get a chance to give their version of events. Mokgalapa and Senkubuge have elected to take leave until the probe is over. READ: DA caucus deliberates on Tshwane mayor scandal Moodey explained the investigation would cover how the recording was obtained, its authenticity and whether the pair brought the party into disrepute. A case of extortion and invasion of privacy has been opened at the Brooklyn SAPS. Meanwhile, the EFF in Tshwane has tabled an urgent motion of no confidence in Mokgalapa. The red berets say Mokgalapa can't fix the problems plaguing the metro. These include an ongoing water crisis, power cuts and wasteful expenditure.